         <abstract>
            <p>When $f(z)$ is given by a known power series expansion, it is possible to construct the power series expansion for $f(z; p) = e^{-pz}f(z)$. We define $p_{opt}$ to be the value of $p$ for which the expansion for $f(z; p)$ converges most rapidly. When $f(z)$ is an entire function of order 1, we show that $p_{opt}$ is uniquely defined and may be characterized in terms of the set of singularities $z_i = 1/\sigma_i$ of an associated function $h(z)$. Specifically, it is the center of the smallest circle in the complex plane which contains all points $\sigma_i$.</p>
          </abstract>
